  "messages": [
    {
      "id": "8c56923a6aad52e38e91850012728c3ca5ffca31",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-01-21 04:47:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nI'm concerned with disabling test 101a. The whole point of that test is to ensure that random reads do NOT read too much data. Even of the readahead code is growing reads initially because it thinks the reads are sequential, it should still be tracking the original read size and if the reads are always random 64kB chunks then growing the reads to 1MB is a lot of overhead.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "3901c7a3dcad0eebf849fc9fade58919914775e2",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 12,
        "name": "wangdi",
        "email": "di.wang@intel.com",
        "username": "wangdi",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-01-21 05:00:21.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHmm, in current implementation, we will extend every small read to 1M, no matter it is random or sequence, i.e. it does not check whether it is initial read or subsequent read of a sequential access. I thought the whole point is that read 1M is always more efficient, since the rpc round time is almost the same no matter how much you will read (4k or 1M)? No? Though client might read some useless pages if it is completely random reads like 101a.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "ce36605c32ac9fb6ab65b6eb186fc5ade3965d7f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-01-21 05:37:04.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nBuild Started http://build.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/4344/ ",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
