    {
      "id": "5efb6e4b7d70aac11c3e494ae7daf117271a47e1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-01-30 09:50:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(2 inline comments)\n\n> I thought the whole point is that read 1M is always more\n> efficient, since the rpc round time is almost the same no\n> matter how much you will read (4k or 1M)?\n\nI think it is a reasonable assumption that files will be read sequentially until shown otherwise, so small files could start with a full 1MB read on first access, and only do smaller reads if the file begins to have random accesses.\n\nHowever, I also think that if the file is seeing random file IO, then reading in full 1MB chunks for every read can cause a lot of overhead and memory wasteage if the reads are small. \n\nDo we have a sanity.sh test for max_read_ahead_whole_mb?  This string doesn't appear in lustre/tests/*.sh, so I suspect not.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "3dc4929f5cb078ab2c1717278996d78af1c312a7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 12,
        "name": "wangdi",
        "email": "di.wang@intel.com",
        "username": "wangdi",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-01-31 06:36:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n\"I think it is a reasonable assumption that files will be read sequentially until shown otherwise, so small files could start with a full 1MB read on first access, and only do smaller reads if the file begins to have random accesses.\n\nHowever, I also think that if the file is seeing random file IO, then reading in full 1MB chunks for every read can cause a lot of overhead and memory wasteage if the reads are small. \"\n\nIn current Master, during the first access, read-ahead will extend to the read_size from syscall (instead of extending to stripe_size as 1.8) . Then if there are sequential accessing in the following read, it will extend the read-ahead window by 1M each time. So we should be ok here?\n\n\"Do we have a sanity.sh test for max_read_ahead_whole_mb? This string doesn't appear in lustre/tests/*.sh, so I suspect not.\"\n\nNo, we do not have yet. Sure, I will add one.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
